This was my first time coming to this location. Are usually go to the location on Webster Street but there was a mixup, but everything worked out just fine. It's always hard finding a good vet clinic to take your pets to because you want to feel comfortable and confident since you rely on them to make sure your pet is healthy and in good hands. This is the place to go and BOTH locations are great.

PROS
-Easy appointment booking online or calling.
-Staff is so friendly, patient, understanding and helpful.
-easy drop off appointment due to Covid safety. Just park in the spot, call the front desk and let them know what space number you are in. Easy.
-good location
-Clean office
-They do NOT try to gouge you with unnecessary services or medications. I've had bad experiences with other vet clinics before with my other dog.
-I feel comfortable and always have a peace of mind whenever I take my pet here.
-I have had to book with different veterinarian doctors so I could get the soonest appointment, but they all were great and just all consistently good. :) My last two visits were with Dr. Thurman and she was outstanding. Very thorough and patient when explaining things I wasn't sure about.< /text>

<Name>RE Casper</Name><text>This recognition is long time past due, but no less true today than it was when we first walked through the door.‚Ä®‚Ä® In short‚Ä¶ knowledgable, capable, kind, caring and compassionate could all be used to describe this place in our experience.

Long form‚Ä¶ In 2012, our family moved here from the midwest and we are quite fond of our family furball. But, being a full on terrier, he's never without a daredevilish bump or bruise now and then. These things considered, finding a family vet was of high priority.

Fortunately we landed in Alameda when we made the leap out here, and discovered Dr. Wooley at Providence. A meeting that lead to a life saving event for our dog.

He had an episode late one night and we took him in to get checked out at the VCA Emergency Vet down in San Leandro (24hrs and very good as well). While there, they took some biopsies and, well, he tested positive for cancer in a spot on his neck.

We went through the process with VCA... got the diagnosis, treatment options, prices, stomach churning budget realities, hard discussions, tears, the works... Around that time, during a check-up with Dr. Wooley, she stepped in and offered to conduct the procedure herself and in doing so, proved spectacular. The bad bits were removed and the follow-ups were all negative. He was 9 at the time... As of this writing, he is 11yrs young and still dashing around the house with sporadic bursts of terrier energy.

He's got wear on his tires, of course, but no matter what, his life was saved that summer and every new year we have with him is a year given to us by Dr. Wooley and Providence Vet.

We like to think our little dude is equally as appreciative, as any time we walk near the place, he pulls us toward the door, begging to get in. Sometimes I think he's more excited to go to the vet, than he is to go home.

Our deepest thanks and highest recommendation.<//text><user_id>108201505701156348249< /user_id>< Rating>

<UserId.>115262100651502957678< /UserId.><gmap_id>0x80da2d79ad0bc30d:0x7dfaf9f91969bb4b< /gmap_id><Review>Normally I would give this 4-5 stars, but we just stopped there tonight to take a restroom break from long driving, and it was completely pitch black.  There was a faint light in the Ranger's kiosk.  There didn't appear to be any campers at all.
We used flashlights to get to the restroom and go inside, and there was a black widow spider on the door, and one busy making it's web by the toilet.
We used another one, and there were two spiders in the toilet, not black widows, or maybe juveniles.
The whole experience was kind of scary, and, with no safety lights near the bathroom or anywhere in the campground, there's the possibility of getting too close to a rattlesnake at the bathrooms as well.
There weren't any notices or anything explaining why it was completely, totally dark aside from the faint light in the ranger's kiosk.
No overnight camping right now?  I don't know.
It was very eerie.</Review>< rating>

< text>
Decent campground with clean bathroom facilities. Camp sites are very close to one another but luckily our neighbors were respectful//quiet. I was disappointed there was no camp host to buy firewood from when I arrived around 5 pm. Campground is nestled between two roads so it can be pretty loud at night with passing cars. If you are looking for a desert feel, this might not be best campground for you.<//text>

<pics>None</pics><GmapID>0x80da2d79ad0bc30d:0x7dfaf9f91969bb4b< /GmapID><response>None<//response>< Text>
Cabins are a great "step up" from a tent, especially in the 30-40 mph winds we had the last few days (early April).
No power nearby and there are a few water taps scattered around the campground (not drinkable).

The Calif. Parks staff here are very knowledgeable of the area.

My only gripe is the showers - water is  only luke-warm. They have a token machine that takes $1, $5, $10 and $20 bills.< /Text>

<Text>Great facilities. Clean and always stocked bathrooms. The only negative was the proximity to the highway (albeit not a very busy highway) and overhead power lines along the south side of the campgrounds. Showers are run by tokens (token machine conveniently located right outside the showers): 25 cents per token for 2 minutes of water. Water was very warm but pressure dropped to dismal levels when there's more than one shower running. Bundles of firewood are conveniently sold by the friendly Rangers at the front station for $6. Overall it was pretty great and I'd love to go back and visit again.</Text>< user_id>

< userid>
102026985458587560660</userid>
< text>
A five star California State Campground. From tent sites to cabins. It is located in the Yaqui Wells area, which is a protected aquifer withing the Anza Borrego Desert State Park. There is also the free Yaqui Wells campground next door, so if this smaller sized full service (for a rustic state park) campground has no space for you, then you can stay for free in the open site camping next door, mere walking distance. Amazing during wildflower and cactus flower seasons of course, and a good place to enjoy winter camping, or test yourself in the extremes of summer camping. The overall intensity of this park is amazing - most of the year it is an impressively malevolent place - although you can find balmy days for a few weeks here and there.</text>

<user_name>Jorge Fernandez</user_name><Resp>None</Resp><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPNyKNPm41ICOOskEWKj3ENjZLB1ojIuIQXPWO8=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNvL9mjpvKG3JvS7t5RN5A2H1BFnbHqZGqkGV3D=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOq3x26hYnCXxzZct2PY64YBT9MtxW027HXjsvc=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO0MXWBo5D5Kr4i_-3SIh5eeV4Fmu4g7sbI4-TU=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pics><Date>1547856410857</Date><Rate>5<//Rate>< text>
Very friendly staff! They were very informative of nearby things to see and do. They even helped us jump start our battery on our way out. When you check in you get a parking pass that gives you access to other day use trails and the like throughout Anza Borrego and a key to lock/unlock the cabin if your site has one.

The camp grounds themselves are very clean. There's dumpsters/recycling on site to toss your trash when you're done. Ideally we all pack in and pack out but in the event you might miss something, I saw rangers going around picking things up too. At night you can see the sky very clearly. Only complaint is the road is not far off so you will hear cars from time to time.

As for amenities, it's more than enough. Camp site has a partially covered picnic table. There's a fire pit at each site with a retractable grill piece. Some sites have small stand up grills. Non potable water access is available at various locations throughout the campsite. Bathrooms near the campsite entrance. They have dim lights on at night so you can see. Showers have hot water but it takes a bit to heat up if it's cold and hasn't been on (50 cents per two minutes of water). Cabin itself is pretty bare. If you don't set up a tent outside, you'll find three bunks in the cabin (just the wood frames so bring blankets, pillows, etc if you plan to utilize it). Two twin sized bunks and an attic space about the size of a king bed. There's a small table with two chairs and a few shelves for storage. You could probably fit 5-7 people comfortably in the cabin depending on how close y'all want to be haha<//text>
<gmap_id>0x80da2d79ad0bc30d:0x7dfaf9f91969bb4b<//gmap_id><user_id>103961405597805675642< /user_id></record></dataset><record>

<UserId.>107530002267002619111</UserId.><name>Michael Towne<//name><time>1518986383194< /time>< rate>
5</rate>
<Review>Charming and affordable. $25 for tents, $60 for cabins and only $5 for hikers. Showers (token operated), picnic tables and rustic cabins (no water or electricity). Nearby Cactus Loop Trail is a great short hike, especially as the sun sets. Only 20 min from Borrego Springs. Two primitive campgrounds are nearby if you want to forego the bathrooms, showers and cabins. They are Yaquie Wells and Yaquie Pass. Free camping, but no amenities. This is a splendid surprise. Camp here for relaxation and ease of access to surrounding park.</Review><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMnb5kn2I7ycB7idhF3VX8hOM6v5_jdcXyfRmfU=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMEHMlt4G1foz91XGpjbm2LT9LX9Q7XkeN3i1c1=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMhBw4K0lQET9JU94mMvcITgjjQFBMDA-kXUwNc=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOOAnvDN5f-nZB70053kA02LJc9rKuU0H2i9mHa=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMZ4wStkX-D595PPyAM3ECmcRQ8xlj_x_NINDKr=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pics>< resp>

<Pictures>None</Pictures><Response>None</Response><Text>This was a fantastic little campground.  Took my wife, son, and friend here for one night. We chose an off-season time to go and it as pretty hot in the day, but there were plenty of trees there to keep the sun off you and there was also a beautiful breeze going through this area that just made you comfortable even on a pretty hot day.  The night temperature fell to a perfect temperature probably somewhere in the upper 60s/low 70s.  Only complaint I had is at night the wind really picked up and it got so intense, I could hardly sleep.  Luckily, my 1 year old son slept well.  But the wind got very violent sounding at times.  I guess if you can handle some really loud wind, it would be nice.  It could have been the season with it getting really hot in the day and cooling off at night.  But either way, I really liked this place.< /Text><rate>5< /rate>< user_id>

<rating>4< /rating>< text>
Camped four days in mid-March of '16. Well-maintained campsite in tamarisk grove in the desert proved to be ideal as we enjoyed the spring bloom. Both the Cactus and Yaqui Well hikes, just across the road from the campsite, had explosive color. Brochures and numbered interpretive markers greatly add to the experience.</text>

<Time>1491925051016<//Time><Review>Nice campground. Amenities include - firepit, table, benches, shade over table, bathrooms, showers (pay), sinks (non potable), spigots for washing dishes (non potable). Take caution if you sleep lightly as the campground is bordered by two roads and you will hear cars drive by throughout the night. They sell firewood and water at the entry kiosk but, due to the wildflower bloom, were out of firewood when we were there so maybe come prepared (closest store is in Borrego, 20 minutes away).< /Review>< pics>

< review>
This is a great casual, but nice Vietnamese restaurant.  Our visit was during Dinner.

The food ingredients were fresh, the atmosphere was calm, and service staff attentive.  Everything was very clean, including the service staff wearing gloves.

The chicken dish was good, and Pho was well balanced, but also full of flavor.  Didn't seem like I was ingesting pure MSG.

Finally, this place is good for groups and families.

We arrived early, and shortly after the place filled up.

I recommend and will be back.< /review>

<Rating>5< /Rating>< text>
The Pho Tai was 5 stars for the taste buds. It's all in the soup broth. Anybody who sells Vietnamese noodle soup can serve up thin-sliced raw beef, cold and crunchy bean sprouts, fresh slices of green jalapeno, and mint leaves. That's the simple kid's stuff - no cooking involved! What makes or breaks a bowl of pho is the broth. Vietasia (under new ownership) has a beef soup broth that is dynamite. I won't try to suss out the ingredients by taste and smell, but it is delicious.< /text>

< user_id>
118274036889619905850<//user_id>
< name>
Sol Chapeau< /name>
<date>1499978796702<//date><rate>4< /rate>< Review>
My 15 month old daughter & 17 year old brother loved it here.

Pros:
They are strict about keeping big kids out of the 8 & under section, so my daughter was safe.
Foam pit is fun, but smells like sweat.
Dodgeball is fun, when you don't have a bunch of crazy teenagers. The balls are spongey, so they (usually) don't hurt.
The big trampoline section is fairly large. I had no trouble finding a place to bounce off the walls (literally) without bumping into others.
Both my daughter & my brother fell asleep on the drive home.

Cons:
Wear light clothes, you WILL get hot.
The pads between trampolines are fairly hard. It's better than landing on a steel bar though.<//Review>

< Text>
Sky High is AWESOME!!! I have been here for countless birthdays (not a party) and just for fun. I LOVE dodgeball although some of the bigger stronger guys can throw pretty hard so watch out!!! The trampoline area is big. I like the foam pit but it does smell of sweat. They could change out the blocks a little more often. I did like the original foam pit setup better with three tracks and side trampolines. Other than that, Its pretty fun, safe (as long as you follow the rules and know your own limits and don't try to do anything stupid), and the staff is awesome!!! I would highly recommend it. Wear light clothes, bring lots of water, and for girls, put your hair up very securely!!! Also, jewelry, glasses and hearing aids should go in your shoes in the cubbies!!! They will get lost or damaged!!! Especially while playing dodgeball or jumping into the foam pit!!!< /Text>

<Rating>5< /Rating>< text>
Although the first experience wasn't the best(the main bounce area was being used for a class and the only other place to bounce was the little kids area) it was still fun because of dodgeball.  Also i contacted the general manager Jonathon about what happened and he gave my entire group tickets for free to return.  that is great customer service.  I would highly recommend this place to anyone that wants to have a god time for a few hours.  And its not to expensive.  And for those of you haters that say it is to expensive then realize that there are times where you can jump for cheap.  Also if you broke something(back) while jumping well that is your fault and not the companies.  They post all of the rules and its not their fault if you can't jump into a giant pit.  NOT DANGEROUS.<//text>

< review>
This location only. San Luis Obispo on Los Isis Valley road

I am probably one of Enterprises top non-business customers on the central coast. Just the past year I have rented from them 8x, usually a week to two weeks at a time. In prior years I have rented even more.
On this last rental, I kept the car an additional week because because of a car issue and my uncle had passed. I have kept calls past my original reservation before with no issues. This time was different.

A girl from the SLO office I rented from called one of the contacts I put down when I rented. I believe it was the long Presidents day weekend. So I thought the office would be closed. I had the car past the original reservation but I went to the Santa Maria, CA location to pay $300 for the first week. I went there because it was more convenient, and the lady there was great.
Back to my personal contact information. They called my friend and said they would call the police and report the car as stolen. Remember this was during the long holiday weekend and I never had an issue when I kept the car longer. Anyway, I spent over $600.00 on the rental.
I also had to call AAA on one of the days because the car died, I only called AAA because the Enterprise roadside assistance at, 1am,  would not be out until the next day. So I got credit for a day which I should have been. The girl knew I was not happywith my overall experience, but tried to have me give her a good rating anyways because she took care of the extra day(which should have been done anyway).
I'm just upset that they were going to call the police, when they have my credit card number and all my other info. What kind of car thief leaves all their information????

Other than this rental I have had no problems with Enterprise. I will keep renting, but at another branch.<//review>

<date>1529623371423< /date>< text>
If you're looking for a fancy place to sit down and eat, this is not it. However if you're looking for delicious, authentic Mexican food, this is definitely the place to go.

Small, cozy feel. The owner and the employees are extremely friendly, and the food is possibly some of the best in East LA. I really recommend their burritos as they go a step ahead and use handmade flour tortillas.

Support your community and give this place a try, you will not regret it.<//text>

<rate>5< /rate>< Review>
I suspected my home had termites, and requested a termite inspection.  The Orkin inspector quickly identified the issue as crickets, not termites.  I was relieved.  The home damages and costs associated with termites vs crickets is huge.  So bonus points to Orkin for not trying to up sell me on termites!

I scheduled Orkin for quarterly home perimeter treatment (crickets plus other insects). I received auto-texts reminding me of the scheduled appointment, a text when the technician  was headed my way, and another text when the tech arrived (these texts are appreciated).  The tech was on-time, professionally dressed, super friendly and informative.  You can tell this tech enjoys his job, which reflects well on the franchise management.

Of note, besides spraying the outside edges of the house and inside the garage (I asked not to spray the home interior for now), he also cleared all cobwebs around the house and patio eaves.  This is his benchmark for future visits to see if spiders are returning or not.  If he sees new webs in the future, he said he‚Äôd treat those areas.  Impressive!!

Overall, with just the one inspection and the one treatment, I‚Äôm totally satisfied!  (And I‚Äôm already seeing crickets scurry from their hiding places!)</Review>
